Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` without binding to a real port. Pair it with the MCP C# SDK's `StreamableHttpClientTransport` (or `SseClientTransport` for older SSE-based servers).

**1. Add packages to your test project:**

```xml
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing" Version="9.0.*" />
<PackageReference Include="ModelContextProtocol" Version="0.2.*" />
```

**2. Write a test:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol.Transport;

public class McpIntegrationTests
    : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
        => _factory = factory;

    [Fact]
    public async Task ListTools_ReturnsExpectedTools()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an HttpClient
        // talking to the in-memory test server
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Wire it into the MCP transport
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                // or whatever your MCP endpoint path is
            },
            httpClient);               // ← pass the test client

        await using var mcpClient =
            await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var tools = await mcpClient.ListToolsAsync();

        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
        Assert.Contains(tools, t => t.Name == "my-tool");
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsCorrectResult()
    {
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
            },
            httpClient);

        await using var mcpClient =
            await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var result = await mcpClient.CallToolAsync(
            "my-tool",
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" });

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
        Assert.Contains("expected output", result.Content[0].Text);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **No real port** — `WebApplicationFactory` uses an in-process `TestServer`. All HTTP goes through an in-memory handler pipeline.
- **Full fidelity** — middleware, DI, routing, auth all run exactly as in production.
- If your server uses the newer **Streamable HTTP** transport instead of SSE, swap to `StreamableHttpClientTransport` with the same `HttpClient` pattern.
- Make `Program` visible to your test project with `InternalsVisibleTo` or a `public partial class Program { }` marker in your server project.
- Override services (e.g. swap a real DB for an in-memory one) using `_factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))`.
